		<header>
			
			<h1>UK beef sector raises concerns over functioning of supply chain </h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the National Beef Association (NBA) in the UK, in view of the dominant role of supermarkets within the supply chain ‘currently prime stock prices cover just 70 per cent of the cost of producing typical slaughter cattle’. As a consequence, ‘hundreds of worried beef farmers are considering throwing in the towel if there is no respite from these persistent losses.’ The NBA is looking at an expansion of exports to EU markets ‘as one way of restoring much needed cost-income balance’, since EU and world markets are ‘already responding to increasingly tight global cattle supplies with significantly stronger cattle prices’.</p><p>There are fears that ‘UK supermarkets may refuse to accept this trend’ and may create a situation where the UK market is insulated from EU and global price developments. This needs to be seen against a background of just four supermarkets controlling 76% of the retail grocery market in the UK.</p><p>The difficulties faced in Argentina in sustaining beef exports (where exports declined 57% in 2010), and the growing orientation of expanding Brazilian beef exports to non-EU markets, would appear to hold out the prospect of improved prices for UK beef farmers, to ease the pressures arising from escalating feed-grain costs.</p><p>This UK position received support from a Copa-Cogeca press statement issued on 9 March, calling on the EC to ensure that livestock value chains function better, in order to ensure a more equitable distribution of prices and margins along the food chain. Calls were also made for an adjustment of EU competition rules to allow cooperatives ‘to grow in size and scale’, thereby ‘contributing to a better balanced food chain’.</p><p>The EU livestock sector is currently seen as facing a profitability squeeze as a result of high input costs, and low and volatile prices. Imports are seen as compounding supply-chain problems, with the EC’s approach to the Mercosur negotiations being subject to particularly fierce criticism (see <i>Agritrade</i>&nbsp;article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Fisheries/Regions" target="_blank">EU farmers release data on concerns over EU-Mercosur negotiations</a>’, April 2011). EU farmers’ leaders have accused Trade Commissioner Karel De Gucht of ‘sacrificing agriculture and particularly the livestock sector in order to secure a Mercosur deal at any cost’.</p>
		
		
